** {{ill|Ichikishima-hime|ja|市杵島姫神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ichikishima-hime|qq=}}
** 

== History ==
The shrine is said to have been established in {{ill|876|ja|876年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/876|qq=}} ({{ill|Jōgan era|ja|貞観|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōgan era|qq=}} 18). It was rebuilt in {{ill|1604|ja|1604年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1604|qq=}} ({{ill|Keichō era|ja|慶長|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Keichō era|qq=}} 8) and again in {{ill|1831|ja|1831st year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1831|qq=}} ({{ill|Tenpō era|ja|天保|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpō era|qq=}} 2).

[[File:Munakata-shrine-torii-chiba-feb21-2016.jpg|thumb|Torii gate]]
== Overview ==
The shrine is regarded as the {{ill|Sōchinju|ja|総鎮守|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sōchinju|qq=}} (chief shrine) of the many Munakata shrines located around the southern edge of the northern plateau by {{ill|Inbanuma|ja|印旛沼|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inbanuma|qq=}}. It is believed to be the oldest shrine among the Munakata shrines in the region. 

Nearby are {{ill|Yakuō-ji (Shiroi)|ja|薬王寺 (白井市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yakuō-ji (Shiroi)|qq=}}, associated with local dragon legends, and {{ill|Benzaiten (Shiroi)|ja|弁財天 (白井市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Benzaiten (Shiroi)|qq=}}.

